		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Concerning slots</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />As far as I know about it, we can divide the CPU memory area used to store ROM PRG into slots. These slots contains pages that are load from the cartridge.
<br />Here is my question : considering a game that uses mapper technology. Can I say for sure that its ROM PRG is divided into slots of same size ?
<br />
<br />For instance, lets take a game that allows 4 slots. Do these slots have have all a size of $2000 bytes?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Dwedit</b> [ Mon Feb 15, 2010 3:04 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Not always.
<br />
<br />Some mappers let you use multiple page sizes, such as MMC1, where you can use either 16K or 32K PRG pages.
<br />Other mappers only let you use one size of page, such as MMC3, where all PRG pages are 8K in size.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


